{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-01811/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-01811"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:18:11"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["medium shot"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["low"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["fixed"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["two shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A man crosses his hand over his chest toward his heart, while speaking to a woman sitting opposite him."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01811/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-01811","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01811/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-01811"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01811/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01811/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01811/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01811/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01811/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01811/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01811/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01811/canvas/1/0e108a1a-6ead-47bc-9437-aa1952988e8a","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-07-01T15:07:20.833Z","creator":"Clara Smith","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Reynolds, of course, is eager to discuss Alma’s mother—and his own. His love for Alma and the way he measures her against the world is always rooted in how she fits into his life as a replacement maternal figure, someone who can care for him in times of distress. He both desires to craft this role for her (an aesthetic act of creation) and wishes for her to take charge.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01811/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:619.5154185022026,90.59471365638764,382.1585903083702,408.33700440528634"}}},{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01811/canvas/1/aed5ce59-1b16-42c7-9450-4479778ae433","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-07-01T15:07:34.718Z","creator":"Clara Smith","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Reynolds’s description of his mother’s hair that he wears in his breast at all times can be understood as another “phantom thread.” It’s something that he has hidden in his clothing and reserves for himself (and those he lets in, such as Alma).&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01811/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:905.2422907488987,655.330396475771,193.83259911894277,262.88546255506606"}}},{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01811/canvas/1/e09a5b78-2570-4d49-af00-5a3bb6505979","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-07-01T15:07:51.304Z","creator":"Clara Smith","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Hair is associated with strength and power in the Biblical story of Samson, in which his strength rested on his uncut hair. On the one hand, the secret inclusion of hair near Reynolds’s heart suggests a desire for power, especially since this is a cut lock of hair. On the other hand, precisely because this is a cut lock of hair, and considering how cutting Samson’s hair voided his superhuman strength, the gesture reveals a desire for control that will eventually give way to a desire to relinquish that very emotion.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01811/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:1188.623348017621,338.5572687224669,150.59471365638774,135.693832599119"}}}]}]}]}